'''Gernot Grabher''' (born 13 April 1960 in [[Dornbirn]], [[Austria]]) is an [[economic geographer]] and Professor of [[Urban economics|Urban]] and [[Regional economics|Regional Economic]] Studies at the [[HafenCity University Hamburg]]. He received his Ph.D. in 1987 at [[Vienna University of Technology]], and held positions at the Wissenschaftszentrum Berlin (WZB), [[King's College London]], the University of Konstanz and the University of Bonn.<ref>https://www.hcu-hamburg.de/en/research/arbeitsgebiete/grabher/</ref> Grabher was Visiting Professor at [[Columbia University]], [[Copenhagen Business School]], [[Santa Fe Institute]], [[Cornell University]] and the Institute of Advanced Study in the Behavioral Sciences.<ref>http://www.coi.columbia.edu/faculty.html#gg {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141208211536/http://www.coi.columbia.edu/faculty.html |date=2014-12-08 }}</ref> Between 2007 and 2011 he was co-editor of [[Economic Geography (journal)|Economic Geography]].<ref>http://www.clarku.edu/econgeography/editors.cfm</ref> Currently, he is co-editor of the Regions and Cities book series of the [[Regional Studies Association]].<ref>http://www.taylorandfrancis.com/books/series/RSA/page_4/</ref> Gernot Grabher is internationally renowned for his research on networks, regional evolution and decline, and project organization.
==Selected works== * (with O. Ibert und S. Flohr) The Neglected King: Consumers in the New Knowledge Ecology of Innovation. In: Economic Geography 84(3), 2008. * Trading Routes, Bypasses, and Risky Intersections: Mapping the Travels of ‘Networks’ between Economic Sociology and Economic Geography. In: Progress in Human Geography 30(2), 2006. * Temporary Architectures of Learning: Knowledge Governance in Project Ecologies. In: Organization Studies 25(9), 2004. * (with [[Walter W. Powell|W. W. Powell]]), Networks. Cheltenham: Edward Elgar (Critical Studies in Economic Institutions Series), 2004. * (with [[David C. Stark|D. Stark]]), Restructuring Networks in Post-Socialism: Legacies, Linkages, and Localities. Oxford: Oxford University Press, 1997. * The Embedded Firm. On the Socioeconomics of Industrial Networks. London and New York: Routledge, 1993.
