{|{{Infobox ship begin}} {{Infobox ship image |Ship image=The Mathew cruising Cardiff Bay (2799993543).jpg |Ship image size=200px |Ship caption=A replica of ''The Matthew'' in Cardiff Bay }} {{Infobox ship career |Hide header= |Ship country=England |Ship flag= |Ship name=The Matthew |Ship namesake= |Ship owner= |Ship operator= |Ship registry= |Ship route= |Ship ordered= |Ship awarded= |Ship builder=[[Bristol Classic Boat Company|Storms'l Services]] |Ship original cost= |Ship yard number= |Ship way number= |Ship laid down=1994 |Ship launched=1996 |Ship sponsor= |Ship christened= |Ship completed= |Ship acquired= |Ship commissioned= |Ship recommissioned= |Ship decommissioned= |Ship maiden voyage= |Ship in service= |Ship out of service= |Ship renamed= |Ship reclassified= |Ship refit= |Ship struck= |Ship reinstated= |Ship homeport=[[Bristol]] |Ship identification= |Ship motto= |Ship nickname= |Ship honours= |Ship captured= |Ship fate= |Ship status= |Ship notes= |Ship badge= }} {{Infobox ship characteristics |Hide header= |Header caption= |Ship class= |Ship type=replica [[caravel]] |Ship tonnage= |Ship displacement= 85 |Ship tons burthen= 50 |Ship length= Length overall: {{convert|78|ft|m|abbr=on}} |Ship beam={{convert|20|ft|6|in|m|abbr=on}} |Ship height={{convert|72.5|ft|6|in|m|abbr=on}} |Ship draught={{convert|7|ft|6|in|m|abbr=on}} |Ship draft= |Ship depth= |Ship hold depth= |Ship decks= 2 |Ship deck clearance= |Ship ramps= |Ship ice class= |Ship power= 200hp Caterpillar 3116 |Ship propulsion= sail, engine |Ship sail plan= caravel |Ship speed= |Ship range= |Ship endurance= |Ship test depth= |Ship boats= |Ship capacity= |Ship troops= |Ship complement= |Ship crew= |Ship time to activate= |Ship sensors= |Ship EW= |Ship armament= |Ship armour= |Ship aircraft= |Ship aircraft facilities= |Ship notes= }} |}
'''''The Matthew''''' is a replica of a [[caravel]]<ref>Also spelled '''''Mathew''''' at the time.</ref> sailed by [[John Cabot]] in 1497 from [[Bristol]] to North America, presumably [[Newfoundland (island)|Newfoundland.]] After a voyage which had got no further than [[Iceland]], Cabot left again with only one vessel, the ''Matthew'', a small ship (50 tons), but fast and able. The crew consisted of only 18 men. ''The Matthew'' departed either 2 May or 20 May 1497. He sailed to [[Dursey Island|Dursey Head]] ([[latitude]] 51°36N), Ireland, from where he sailed due west, expecting to reach Asia. However, landfall was reached in North America on 24 June 1497. His precise landing place is a matter of much controversy, with [[Cape Bonavista]] or [[St. John's, Newfoundland and Labrador|St. John's]] in [[Newfoundland and Labrador|Newfoundland]] the most likely sites.
Cabot went ashore to take possession of the land, and explored the coast for some time, probably departing on 20 July. On the homeward voyage his sailors incorrectly thought they were going too far north, so Cabot sailed a more southerly course, reaching [[Brittany]] instead of England. On 6 August he arrived back in [[Bristol]].
==History== Lack of clear documentation has been a problem in studying the history of ''Matthew''. Even its name has been questioned, with some authors suggesting that it was actually named ''Mattea'' after Cabot's wife.<ref>Wilson, Ian ''John Cabot and the Matthew'' Breakwater Books 2001 {{ISBN|978-1-55081-131-5}} p.22 [https://books.google.com/books?id=_lvr4WKU2YkC&pg=PA22&lpg=PA22&dq=cabot+ship+matthew+name+wife&source=bl&ots=IKQkVfXfpT&sig=2zS50KHg-Z7hjK_tME0C50mMmYQ&hl=en&ei=SMD-SaSlB-HOjAeli-GeAw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=5]</ref> Until the 1950s, all that was known about its size is that it was a small ship carrying about 18 men, but the discovery of a letter from a Bristol merchant named John Day written in 1497 saying that "in his voyage he had only one ship of fifty 'toneles' and twenty men and food for seven or eight months" provided more certainty about its size.<ref name="Jones">[http://ehr.oxfordjournals.org/cgi/content/abstract/CXXI/492/778 'Jones, Evan "The ''Matthew'' of Bristol and the financiers of John Cabot’s 1497 Voyage to North America" ''English Historical Review'' Vol. CXXI No. 492 (2006)']</ref> The age of the ship is also uncertain. The name ''Matthew'' does not appear in the 1492/3 customs accounts, so it was either fairly new or an older ship renamed or a foreign ship. It has been suggested that it probably was an ordinary Bristol merchant ship hired for the occasion. The name ''Matthew'' appears in documents in 1503/04 and 1510/11 but in a 1513 survey there is reference to a 'new Matthew' and references to this ship afterward leave out the 'new' suggesting that Cabot's ''Matthew'' no longer existed.<ref name="Jones"/>
== Replica ==
[[File:The Matthew Dec09 side view.jpg|thumb|''Matthew'' replica moored in Bristol]]
To celebrate the 500th anniversary of Cabot's voyage, a replica of ''Matthew'' was built in Bristol by Storms'l Services, a precursor of the [[Bristol Classic Boat Company]]. The design was by naval architect Colin Mudie. She was dedicated in a ceremony during the first [[International Festival of the Sea, 1996|International Festival of the Sea]], held in Bristol's [[Bristol Harbour|Floating Harbour]] in 1996. The next year, she reconstructed Cabot's original journey on the 500th anniversary of the landmark voyage. On 24 June 1997 the replica of ''Matthew'' was welcomed into port at Bonavista by [[Elizabeth II of the United Kingdom|Queen Elizabeth II]].
The full-size replica<ref>{{cite web | title=Building the Matthew | work=The Matthew of Bristol | url=http://www.matthew.co.uk/building.php | accessdate=26 October 2008 | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080807013049/http://www.matthew.co.uk/building.php | archivedate=7 August 2008 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> is {{convert|78|ft|m|abbr=on}} in length overall with a beam of {{convert|20|ft|6|in|m|abbr=on}} with a draft of {{convert|7|ft|m|abbr=on}} and {{convert|2360|sqft|m2|0|abbr=on}} of sail.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Matthew Statistics |work=The Matthew of Bristol |url=http://www.matthew.co.uk/ship_statistics/statistics.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060112195828/http://www.matthew.co.uk/ship_statistics/statistics.html |archivedate=12 January 2006 |accessdate=20 August 2006 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref>
On 29 February 2012 ''Matthew'''s ownership was transferred to The Matthew of Bristol Trust, and she was relocated to her new home outside Bristol's [[M Shed]] museum.<ref name=thisisbristol-20120229>{{cite news |url=http://www.thisisbristol.co.uk/New-trust-takes-helm-replica-Matthew/story-15350416-detail/story.html |title=New trust takes the helm of replica Matthew |newspaper=Bristol Evening Post |date=29 February 2012 |accessdate=29 February 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120302225239/http://www.thisisbristol.co.uk/New-trust-takes-helm-replica-Matthew/story-15350416-detail/story.html |archivedate=2 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>
In June 2012 she took part in the [[Diamond Jubilee of Elizabeth II|Queen's Diamond Jubilee]] pageant on the [[River Thames]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Bristol celebrates Queen's Diamond Jubilee |website=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-bristol-18297797 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120606002039/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-bristol-18297797 |archivedate=6 June 2012 |accessdate=6 May 2012 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref>
